{"id":"1602.08461","submitter":"Lei You","authors":"Lei You, Jianbo Li, Changjiang We, Chenqu Dai","title":"A One-Hop Information Based Geographic Routing Protocol for Delay\n  Tolerant MANETs","comments":"14 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.NI cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Delay and Disruption Tolerant Networks (DTNs) may lack continuous network\nconnectivity. Routing in DTNs is thus a challenge since it must handle network\npartitioning, long delays, and dynamic topology. Meanwhile, routing protocols\nof the traditional Mobile Ad hoc NETworks (MANETs) cannot work well due to the\nfailure of its assumption that most network connections are available. In this\narticle, a geographic routing protocol is proposed for MANETs in delay tolerant\nsituations, by using no more than one-hop information. A utility function is\ndesigned for implementing the under-controlled replication strategy. To reduce\nthe overheads caused by message flooding, we employ a criterion so as to\nevaluate the degree of message redundancy. Consequently a message redundancy\ncoping mechanism is added to our routing protocol. Extensive simulations have\nbeen conducted and the results show that when node moving speed is relatively\nlow, our routing protocol outperforms the other schemes such as Epidemic, Spray\nand Wait, FirstContact in delivery ratio and average hop count, while\nintroducing an acceptable overhead ratio into the network.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 26 Feb 2016 20:07:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 21 Jun 2017 22:31:19 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-06-23"}
{"id":"1602.08462","submitter":"Adrian Melott","authors":"Adrian L. Melott, Brian C. Thomas, Claude M. Laird, Ben Neuenswander,\n  and Dimitra Atri","title":"Atmospheric ionization by high-fluence, hard spectrum solar proton\n  events and their probable appearance in the ice core archive","comments":"JGR Atmospheres, in press","journal-ref":"JGR Atmospheres 121 (2016)","doi":"10.1002/2015JD024064","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ao-ph astro-ph.EP astro-ph.IM astro-ph.SR physics.geo-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Solar energetic particles ionize the atmosphere, leading to production of\nnitrogen oxides. It has been suggested that some such events are visible as\nlayers of nitrate in ice cores, yielding archives of energetic, high fluence\nsolar proton events (SPEs). There has been controversy, due to slowness of\ntransport for these species down from the upper stratosphere; past numerical\nsimulations based on an analytic calculation have shown very little ionization\nbelow the mid stratosphere. These simulations suffer from deficiencies: they\nconsider only soft SPEs and narrow energy ranges; spectral fits are poorly\nchosen; with few exceptions secondary particles in air showers are ignored.\nUsing improved simulations that follow development of the proton-induced air\nshower, we find consistency with recent experiments showing substantial excess\nionization down to 5 km. We compute nitrate available from the 23 February 1956\nSPE, which had a high fluence, hard spectrum, and well-resolved associated\nnitrate peak in a Greenland ice core. For the first time, we find this event\ncan account for ice core data with timely (~ 2 months) transport downward\nbetween 46 km and the surface, thus indicating an archive of high fluence, hard\nspectrum SPE covering the last several millennia. We discuss interpretations of\nthis result, as well as the lack of a clearly-defined nitrate spike associated\nwith the soft-spectrum 3-4 August 1972 SPE. We suggest that hard-spectrum SPEs,\nespecially in the 6 months of polar winter, are detectable in ice cores, and\nthat more work needs to be done to investigate this.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 26 Feb 2016 20:07:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-28"}
